    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Email warm-up</strong> is the gradual process of increasing send volume from a new or dormant IP address or domain to establish trust with mailbox providers before reaching full-scale sending. It typically runs 4 to 8 weeks, starts with 50-200 daily sends to the most engaged subscribers, and doubles roughly every few days while monitoring bounce and complaint rates.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Duration</div>
            <div class="tms-value">4-8 weeks</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Email Marketing</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Skip cost</div>
            <div class="tms-value">3+ months recovery</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Intermediate</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Every new sender starts with zero reputation at Gmail, Outlook, and Yahoo. Blast 50,000 cold emails on day one and mailbox providers treat you as a spammer. Warm up correctly and you reach 90+ percent inbox placement by week eight. Skip it and you spend the next three months digging out.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is email warm-up?</h2>
        <p>Email warm-up is a scheduled sending ramp that trains mailbox providers to trust a new IP address, subdomain, or sending domain. Every mailbox provider — Gmail, Outlook, Yahoo, Apple Mail — maintains an internal reputation score per sender. A cold sender starts near zero. Warm-up moves that score to "trusted" through controlled positive signals: high open rates, low bounces, minimal complaints.</p>
        <p>Three assets need warming, not just one:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>IP address</strong> — the network address your ESP sends from.</li>
          <li><strong>Sending domain</strong> — the friendly-from and return-path domains.</li>
          <li><strong>Subdomain</strong> — dedicated subdomains like send.yourbrand.com.</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Authentication first, then volume</div>
          <p>Configure SPF, DKIM, and DMARC before the first warm-up send. Gmail's 2024 bulk-sender rules require SPF and DKIM alignment plus DMARC for any sender pushing 5,000+ messages a day.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why email warm-up matters</h2>
        <p>Three reasons every serious email program invests the weeks:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Inbox placement.</strong> New senders without warm-up see inbox rates of 20-30 percent in month one. Warmed senders hit 90+ percent by week 4-6.</li>
          <li><strong>Reputation persistence.</strong> Mailbox providers weight the last 30 days of behaviour more heavily. A bad first month lingers for a quarter — sometimes longer.</li>
          <li><strong>ESP account safety.</strong> Klaviyo, Mailchimp, HubSpot, and SendGrid monitor first-week send patterns. Volume spikes from cold accounts trigger reviews or suspensions.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How email warm-up actually works</h2>
        <p>The mechanism is Bayesian: mailbox providers form a prior belief about your sender identity based on early sends, then update as more data arrives. Positive signals build the prior; negative signals collapse it. The warm-up schedule engineers positive signals first.</p>

        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># Week 1-2 — Foundation</span><br>
          Day 1-3: <span class="uf-new">50-100 emails/day</span> to most engaged (opened in last 30 days)<br>
          Day 4-7: <span class="uf-new">100-200/day</span> · monitor Postmaster Tools daily<br>
          <br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># Week 3-4 — Scale</span><br>
          Double volume every 2-3 days: <span class="uf-new">400 → 800 → 1,600 → 3,200/day</span><br>
          Target: bounce &lt;2% · complaints &lt;0.1% · open &gt;25%<br>
          <br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># Week 5-8 — Broaden</span><br>
          Add less-engaged segments in 20% increments<br>
          Approach full daily volume by week 6-8
        </div>

        <h3>Dedicated vs shared IP paths</h3>
        <p>A dedicated IP requires full warm-up. A shared IP typically inherits pool reputation but still benefits from a gradual first-two-weeks ramp to build per-sender reputation.</p>

        <h3>Domain warm-up (the newer priority)</h3>
        <p>Mailbox providers moved from IP-reputation to domain-reputation as the primary signal around 2020. That is why warming the sending domain matters even on shared IP pools.</p>

        <h2 id="types">Types of warm-up schedule</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
