        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real warm-up examples</h2>
        <p>Two production scenarios and the schedule each used.</p>

        <h3>1. SaaS ESP migration (Mailchimp to Klaviyo)</h3>
        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># 6-week warm-up · target 40k daily</span><br>
          Wk 1: <span class="uf-new">100 → 500/day</span> to 30-day openers<br>
          Wk 2: <span class="uf-new">500 → 2,500/day</span> · add 60-day openers<br>
          Wk 3: <span class="uf-new">2,500 → 10,000/day</span> · add 90-day openers<br>
          Wk 4-5: <span class="uf-new">10k → 30k/day</span> · add 180-day segment<br>
          Wk 6: <span class="uf-new">30k → 40k/day</span> · full list<br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># Result: 96% inbox placement at week 6</span>
        </div>

        <h3>2. New DTC brand — cold list launch</h3>
        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># 4-week warm-up · target 8k daily</span><br>
          Wk 1: <span class="uf-new">50/day</span> to double-opt-in subscribers only<br>
          Wk 2: <span class="uf-new">50 → 400/day</span> · welcome flow live<br>
          Wk 3: <span class="uf-new">400 → 2,500/day</span> · first promo send<br>
          Wk 4: <span class="uf-new">2,500 → 8,000/day</span> · full campaign volume
        </div>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Warm-up vs deliverability audit — different jobs</h2>
        <p>Warm-up builds reputation on a new asset. A deliverability audit diagnoses reputation problems on an existing asset. Both matter, and both use the same underlying signals — but they solve opposite problems.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Use warm-up when</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>New IP, subdomain, or ESP</li>
              <li>Dormant sender restarting</li>
              <li>Migrating from one ESP to another</li>
              <li>Reputation reset after a block</li>
              <li>Launching a new product line domain</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Use deliverability audit when</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Open rate dropped without list change</li>
              <li>Sudden increase in Promotions placement</li>
              <li>Spam complaints rising</li>
              <li>Gmail Postmaster reputation degrading</li>
              <li>Bounces spiking on a stable list</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">7 best practices for email warm-up</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Set SPF, DKIM, DMARC before day one.</strong> Missing authentication makes every warm-up send weaker.</li>
          <li><strong>Start with your most engaged subscribers.</strong> 30-day openers first. Their opens teach mailbox providers you send wanted mail.</li>
          <li><strong>Send at consistent times.</strong> Same window each day. Reputation forms around predictable patterns.</li>
          <li><strong>Double volume every 2-3 days maximum.</strong> Faster ramps trigger volume-spike filters.</li>
          <li><strong>Monitor bounce and complaint rates daily.</strong> Bounces above 2 percent or complaints above 0.1 percent mean pause and diagnose.</li>
          <li><strong>Use Gmail Postmaster Tools and Microsoft SNDS.</strong> Free per-mailbox-provider dashboards showing exactly what they see.</li>
          <li><strong>Do not send promotional content in weeks 1-2.</strong> Welcome, transactional, and editorial content only. Save promos for week 3+.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — front-loading dormant subscribers</div>
          <p>If your list has not received email in 6 months, warming up to the whole list is deliverability suicide. Half will bounce or complain. Start with only 30-day openers. Add older segments in week 4+ once reputation is set.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common warm-up mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Skipping authentication</strong> — no SPF, DKIM, or DMARC means the reputation ceiling stays low.</li>
          <li><strong>Volume spikes</strong> — 100 emails on Monday, 10,000 on Wednesday guarantees filtering.</li>
          <li><strong>Sending to old lists first</strong> — dormant subscribers bounce or mark spam.</li>
          <li><strong>Mixing promotional and warm-up sends</strong> — send transactional and welcome content only in weeks 1-2.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring Postmaster data</strong> — Gmail tells you exactly when reputation drops. Watch it daily.</li>
          <li><strong>Cutting warm-up short</strong> — hitting week 3 numbers on day 10 undoes the whole schedule.</li>
        </ul>

